      <link>/wiaposts/What-is-renunciation/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Sep 2024 08:33:00 +0530</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>/wiaposts/What-is-renunciation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;/assets/images/wiapost/5265-What-is-renunciation.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;What is Renunciation?&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;What is Renunciation? 
    &lt;div id=&#34;what-is-renunciation&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#what-is-renunciation&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In Sanskrit, there are two words: &lt;em&gt;Sanyasa&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Tyaga&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
People in the English-speaking world think both mean renunciation.&lt;br&gt;
They are related but not the same.&lt;br&gt;
Here, I am talking about &lt;em&gt;Tyaga&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Have you seen these people?&lt;br&gt;
Who are in the ICU and say,
&amp;ldquo;I have renounced food and &lt;em&gt;Sansara&lt;/em&gt; for a few days.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
Who are heartbroken by a partner or friend and say,
&amp;ldquo;I have renounced him/her.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
A 25-year-old man saying,
&amp;ldquo;I have renounced playing with toys.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
A 10-year-old boy who says,
&amp;ldquo;I have renounced playing with mud and my own potty.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
These events happens automatically&lt;br&gt;
Some because of circumstance&lt;br&gt;
and other because of maturity.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
